%S A395036 1,2,0,1000,11898,168070,2460375,36489413,563360716,9050928704,
%T A395036 149717394015,2544415270794,44256681798848,785359541529936,
%U A395036 14186723693086768,260322239654940744,4844275080073344096,91287542044806539824,1739903773941034279488
%N A395036 a(n) is the number of different ways in which three particles move on a triangular grid ABC of side length n, each from one corner to the next, changing direction at each grid point, such that the distance from the starting point is always increasing, and no two particles ever meet.
%C A395036 The particles start at the same moment, one in each corner, and all move at the same constant speed along the grid lines.
%C A395036 Let ABC be an equilateral triangular grid of side n containing n^2 unit equilateral triangles. X axis is defined along AB and Y axis is defined along AC such that starting point A has coordinates (0,0), finishing point B has coordinates (n,0) and C is at (0,n).
%C A395036 A grid point (x,y) on a path of a point P moving from A to B satisfies the following conditions when generating string of coordinates of grid points on a valid path.
%C A395036 x + y <= n, y <= n/2 and x^2 + y^2 + x*y should increase when moving to the next grid point. As P moves from one grid point to the next x remains unchanged or increased by 1 unit. If x does not change y should increase by 1 unit, if x increases by 1 unit y should remain unchanged or decreased by 1 unit. Any three consecutive grid points of a string cannot have same x coordinates or same y coordinates.
%C A395036 Each of P-path from A to B gives a unique S-path from B to C and R-path from C to A by transforming a grid point (h, k) on P-path into (n-h-k, h) on S-path and into (k,n-h-k) on R-path. Any two grid paths do not meet if r-th coordinate of one path is different from r-th coordinate of the other. The r-th and (r+1)-th coordinates of one grid path must not appear swapped in another at positions r and r+1. Paths do not need to have equal length.
%H A395036 Janaka Rodrigo, <a href="/A395036/a395036.txt">Python Code for triplets of grid paths</a>
%e A395036 n = 2 has 2 different ways of moving from A->B, B->C and C->A:
%e A395036 Grid paths from A to B:
%e A395036   P1:{(0,0), (0,1), (1,1), (2,0)},
%e A395036   P2:{(0,0), (1,0), (1,1), (2,0)}.
%e A395036 Grid paths from B to C:
%e A395036   S1:{(2,0), (1,0), (0,1), (0,2)},
%e A395036   S2:{(2,0), (1,1), (0,1), (0,2)}.
%e A395036 Grid paths from C to A:
%e A395036   R1:{(0,2), (1,1), (1,0), (0,0)},
%e A395036   R2:{(0,2), (0,1), (1,0), (0,0)}.
%e A395036 Set of valid triplets of grid paths:
%e A395036   {(P1,S1,R1), (P2,S2,R2)}
%e A395036 Therefore a(2) = 2.
%Y A395036 Cf. A394698, A393490, A343307.
